I too greatly enjoy video and broadcast-style SCPs, and for that reason (in addition to the fact that it's executed well) I am giving this an upvote. However, I have a couple of nitpicks:



Addendum to Containment Procedures ██/██/20██: From this point forward, stop testing this thing on D-class subjects. We’ve wasted a dozen so far, and the only anomalous effect on them has been radiation poisoning. —O5-█
附加记录：    

This may be thing where I'm just trying to force my own headcanon, but I don't see why an O5 would get directly involved in something like that. This is a Safe-class object which, while lethal and disturbing, doesn't seem to represent an especially dire threat in relation to other SCPs, and I would think that the Research Director or perhaps even a Site Director would take care of this issue.



When SCP-719-1 is in place, and SCP-719 is supplied power and turned on, SCP-719-1 will radiate electromagnetic radiation in various spectra including visible light, ultraviolet, [REDACTED], [REDACTED] and a substantial band in [REDACTED]. About 60% of emissions are ionizing radiation.
附加记录：    

I have no idea what you're doing with the redactions here. Are there classified portions of the electromagnetic spectrum now or something? This, to me, was a dissonant note in an otherwise well-written article.

On the more positive side, I kind of like the fact that it's a  cult, but not like some cheesy horror-movie style one.

Also:



■External scenes will gradually become brighter, night becomes day, clouds vanish, and the sun— when visible— will grow progressively larger and whiter.
附加记录：    

I don't know what your Photoshop skillz are like (mine are nonexistent or I would attempt it myself), but a picture in the article depicting this stage of the broadcast, IMHO, would look extremely badass and add a lot to the article.

Overall, good work.







